Rethinking the classic HTTP service pattern now that resource() and httpResource() exist

8 min read
Just now

--

Introduction
For years, every mid-to-large Angular codebase had some version of the same file: a DataService (or ApiService, or HttpFacade) with a couple of generic methods like apiGet(endpoint, params) and apiPost(endpoint, data), each returning an Observable. It was clean, DRY, and every component just injected the service and subscribed. This pattern survived multiple major Angular versions because RxJS Observables were flexible enough to represent literally any network call.
Now Angular has signals, and with them, two new primitives: resource() and its HTTP-flavored sibling, httpResource(). They promise to eliminate the boilerplate of loading flags, error state, and manual subscription management. Naturally, the question becomes: should we keep the old generic data-service pattern, just swapped to return signals instead of Observables?

• Should we still centralize network calls in a generic data service, now built around httpResource?

• httpResource can technically send a POST request — so why does Angular tell us not to use it for mutations?

• Why not just build one generic factory method that takes reactive params and hands back an httpResource reference?

• Is calling that factory method actually happening in a valid “injection context”?

• Why does resource() need an injection context in the first place?
Let’s go through each one.

1. Should we keep the generic data-service pattern?
Not in its original form. The old pattern worked because Observables are cold and generic — apiGet(endpoint, param) could hand back an Observable<T> for anything, and the component decided when (or whether) to subscribe.
resource() and httpResource() don't behave like that. They are:

• Reactive — the request automatically re-fires whenever a signal it reads changes.

• Eager — unlike HttpClient, which waits for a subscriber, a resource fires the moment it's created.

• Stateful — a resource is a live object with value(), error(), isLoading(), and reload(), not a stream you subscribe to repeatedly.
A resource is meant to be created once, in a reactive context, and live for as long as that context does. That rules out a single maximally generic apiGet-style method as the primary interface. Instead, the pattern that holds up is a service that owns what gets fetched and how it's typed, while exposing either a shared resource or a factory method per entity that the component calls with its own reactive parameters:
@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class UserService {
private http = inject(HttpClient); // Shared resource — one instance for the whole app
readonly usersResource = httpResource<User[]>(() => '/api/users');
// Factory — component supplies reactive params, service owns URL/typing
createUserResource(userId: Signal<string | undefined>) {
return httpResource<User>(() =>
userId() ? `/api/users/${userId()}` : undefined
);
}
// Mutations to database stay on plain HttpClient — no resource involved
updateUser(id: string, data: Partial<User>) {
return this.http.put<User>(`/api/users/${id}`, data, { withCredentials: true });
}
}
@Component({ /* ... */ })
export class UserDetailComponent {
private userService = inject(UserService);
userId = input.required<string>(); user = this.userService.createUserResource(this.userId);
}
Components stay focused on rendering, the service owns endpoint knowledge and typing, and each resource still gets its own explicit reactive function — which is what Angular actually needs to track dependencies correctly.

2. httpResource can send a POST — so why avoid it for mutations?
This is the part that trips people up, because it sounds like a rule imposed for no technical reason. It isn’t. The problem isn’t the network call itself — it’s what a resource represents and how its lifecycle is wired.
resource() and httpResource() model "a value that should stay in sync with some reactive inputs." That contract has consequences that are actively harmful for a mutation:

• It’s eager and auto-retriggering. A resource fires the instant it’s created, and again every time a dependency signal changes. A mutation should fire exactly once, deliberately — when a user clicks “Save” — not automatically because some unrelated signal happened to change.

• It auto-cancels in-flight requests. If a dependency changes mid-request, the resource cancels the old request and starts a new one — switchMap-like behavior. That’s harmless for a GET: cancelling and re-reading loses nothing. It’s dangerous for a POST: cancelling a half-sent “create order” and firing a new one can leave you unsure whether the first request actually landed, or worse, cause a duplicate.

• The vocabulary doesn’t fit. What would reload() or error() even mean for a POST? "Reload" implies "re-run the same read." Silently re-running the last write on some lifecycle trigger is not something you want.
So it’s not that httpResource is technically incapable of sending a POST — it's that a declarative, auto-reactive, auto-cancelling primitive is the wrong shape for an imperative, one-shot, non-idempotent action. The Angular team is explicit about this in both the docs and the resource RFC discussion: httpResource is designed for fetching, not for imperative mutation requests.
The practical split:
// GET — resource, reactive, auto-refetches on dependency change
user = httpResource(() => `/api/users/${this.userId()}`);// POST — plain HttpClient, imperative, fires once when called
saveUser(data: User) {
return this.http.post<User>('/api/users', data, { withCredentials: true })
.pipe(tap(() => this.userResource.reload())); // explicitly refresh the read
}
The mutation is a deliberate action, triggered on click, using HttpClient directly. The read that should reflect the new state is a resource, and you explicitly call .reload() on it after the mutation succeeds. That's the modern replacement for the old "manually refetch after save" logic.
3. Why not just build one generic factory that returns a resource ref?
You basically can — and it’s not far from what’s shown above. But pushing it all the way to a single generic method for every endpoint runs into two real problems.
a) Injection context. httpResource() must be called either inside an active injection context (a field initializer, a constructor, or another resource's factory) or with an explicit injector passed in. The old pattern let you call apiGet(...) from anywhere — a click handler, ngOnInit, a deeply nested method — because only the subscription mattered, not the moment of creation. A resource is a stateful object that has to be instantiated at the right point in a component's lifecycle. Push it fully generic and every call site outside a constructor now has to manually thread an Injector through, which doesn't remove boilerplate — it just relocates it.
b) Genericity buys less than it used to. The real value of the old apiGet<T> was URL-building and shared HTTP options. A maximally generic resource factory:
createResource<T>(requestFn: () => string | HttpResourceRequest | undefined) {
return httpResource<T>(requestFn, { injector: this.injector });
}adds almost nothing over calling httpResource() directly, since you still write a distinct reactive function and type parameter at every call site anyway. The value that does accumulate is per-entity: response typing, base URLs, auth headers, error mapping. That's why one factory method per entity (createUserResource, createOrdersResource) is the pattern that holds up — not one universal method for every endpoint, which also still can't help with mutations at all.

4. Is createUserResource(userId) actually running in an injection context?
This is the subtle part: injection context isn’t a property of the method or the class it’s written in — it’s a property of the call stack at the exact moment httpResource() executes. Angular simply checks: is there a currently active injector on this call stack right now?
@Component({ /* ... */ })
export class UserDetailComponent {
private userService = inject(UserService);
userId = input.required<string>(); // ✅ Field initializer — runs during component construction,
// which IS an injection context.
user = this.userService.createUserResource(this.userId);
}
This works because field initializers execute as part of the class constructor, and Angular maintains an active injection context for the entire constructor of any DI-managed class. The chain — constructor → field initializer → createUserResource() → httpResource() — stays on one synchronous call stack, so it's valid even though httpResource() is textually defined inside a different class.
It breaks the moment creation happens later:
export class UserDetailComponent {
private userService = inject(UserService);
user?: HttpResourceRef<User | undefined>; ngOnInit() {
// ❌ ngOnInit runs after construction — no active injection context.
this.user = this.userService.createUserResource(this.userId); // throws
}
}
Rule of thumb: assigning a resource as a field initializer or in a constructor needs no extra work. Creating one lazily — inside ngOnInit, a click handler, or any imperative callback — requires capturing an Injector up front.
5. Why does resource() need an injection context at all?
This isn’t an arbitrary restriction — it’s the mechanism behind two things resources give you for free.
It needs a DestroyRef for automatic cleanup. A resource isn't a one-shot value; it's a live thing holding an in-flight request and watching signals indefinitely. Left unmanaged, it would keep re-fetching for the life of the app. resource() internally injects DestroyRef and registers a cleanup callback, so when its host — the component, directive, or service that created it — is destroyed, the resource automatically cancels its pending request and stops listening. That's how you get "create it and forget it" with no manual ngOnDestroy unsubscribe logic. DestroyRef can only be resolved from an active injector, so without one, there's no way to know whose lifecycle the resource should attach to.
It needs an injector for reactive scheduling — and httpResource needs it for HttpClient too. Internally, resource() sets up something akin to an effect() that re-runs the request whenever a dependency changes. Effects need to be registered against a specific injector's environment to be scheduled and cleaned up correctly. httpResource() additionally needs to inject HttpClient itself to make the request at all — same requirement, same reason.
If resource() didn't need an injection context, it also couldn't auto-attach to a component's destruction, and you'd be back to calling .destroy() by hand — exactly the manual bookkeeping signals were introduced to eliminate. Passing an explicit { injector } doesn't bypass this requirement; it just tells Angular which lifecycle to attach to, supplied manually instead of inferred from the call stack.

Summary
The old “one generic service, two generic methods, everything returns an Observable” pattern doesn’t map cleanly onto signals, because resource() and httpResource() solve a narrower, more specific problem than Observable did: keeping a read in sync with reactive inputs, complete with automatic lifecycle management. That specificity is exactly why they eliminate so much boilerplate — and exactly why they can't be a drop-in generic replacement for everything HTTP.
The pattern worth adopting:

• Reads → httpResource() (or rxResource() if you need debouncing or existing RxJS operators), created via per-entity factory methods on a service, instantiated in a component's field initializers or constructor wherever possible.

• Writes → plain HttpClient calls, triggered imperatively, followed by an explicit .reload() on the relevant resource to bring reads back in sync.
